In the focus of lectures and seminars are selected passages from Plato's "Timaios" and "Politeia", Plotin's "The Enneads", Aristotle's "Categories" and "Metaphysics", Kant's "Critique of Pure Reason" and "Critique of Judgement", Schleiermacher's "Dialectic" and Hegel's "Phenomenology of the Spirit" and "Lectures on the Philosophy of Religion" (details can be found in the timetable of the course).Objectives/eesmärkid:  Orientation in selected fundamental problems and in ways of reasoning in the history of Western philosophy that contribute to a fruitful study of theology and religious studies.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course a student: - describes selected crucial figures and texts of Western philosophy from a perspective that focuses on philopsophy's multifaceted encounterings with religion and theology ; - has gained a reflected experience of a philosophical approach to religious and theological issues; - has gained a reflected experience of philosophical thinking being conditioned by religious and theological issues;  - has exercised reading of philosophical texsts and discussing them publicly;   - discusses the relevance of philosophy for theology and religious studies.
